(Advanced) Quest 9 - Car Borrowing DApp Capstone Project (Frontend)
Introduction
In Quest 8, we built the backend of our Car Borrowing DApp project. In this quest, we’ll be building a frontend application to allow users to interact with everything that we’ve deployed in Quest 8. 
This frontend application will be built using the React framework and the Ethers.js library. Using the MetaMask wallet, we’ll be able to switch between the merchant account and the customer account to see how both of these roles interact with our frontend application.

Since this quest makes use of the files generated in Quest 8, you’ll need to have completed Quest 8 before embarking on this quest.

For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #hedera-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to:
  • Create a React application that allows users to interact with deployed smart contracts
  • Use Ethers.js to interact with deployed smart contracts
  • Connect MetaMask wallet to a frontend application
  • Submit messages to a topic
  • Associate tokens to accounts
  • Approve an allowance of tokens to be transferred
  • Query for information using Mirror Node APIs
Deliverable
This quest has two deliverables. Follow instructions in Step 16 for more details.
  1. Hashscan URL of your deployed smart contract address in the ‘Description’ box
  2. A screenshot containing your Hashscan block explorer displaying messages of your topic

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to DApps
Decentralized applications (DApps) are applications that run on a decentralized, distributed ledger such as a blockchain. Generally DApps are powered by smart contracts, which are self-executing digital contracts coded into the blockchain that ensure the performance of a contract without relying on a third party. However, DApps built on Hedera can be powered by any of the Hedera native services.
DApps are designed to be open source, trustless, and secure, allowing users to interact with each other without the need for a central authority or intermediary. Some examples of popular DApps include Uniswap, Axie Infinity and Compound.

For our project, we’ve already completed the backend portion in Quest 8 (deployed smart contract and created Topic). In this quest, we’ll be building a frontend interface so that users can interact with the smart contract that we’ve deployed. Let’s go!
Step 2: Introduction to React
As mentioned, we’ll be using a popular web development framework called React to build our frontend application. React is a JavaScript-based framework built by Meta. React is a Client-Side Rendering (CSR) framework that leverages the existing browser to run our scripts. 
Right now, modern browsers are shipped with JavaScript runtimes which allow websites to run JavaScript based code. By using React, it uses the same runtime needed to run websites and makes frontend programming more intuitive. It is flexible, lightweight and extremely easy to pick up.

Although we’ll be using the React framework to build our frontend application, we will not be covering React in depth as it is outside the scope of this quest. Please refer to our ReactJS Basics Learn module if you would like to learn more about React.
Step 3: Introduction to Ethers.js
In this quest, we’re going to use the Ethers.js library to allow our DApp to interact with the smart contract we deployed in the previous quest. But first, let’s find out a bit more about what Ether.js is!
Ethers.js is a JavaScript library for interacting with Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) compatible blockchains. It is designed to simplify the development process of blockchain applications, while also providing a secure, robust API for accessing blockchain data and performing transactions. The library contains tools such as a comprehensive suite of APIs, an intuitive EVM wallet, and a powerful transaction signing framework. 

With Ethers.js, developers can quickly and easily build powerful blockchain applications. By default, Ethers.js alone can’t interact with the Hedera network. However, due to the JSON RPC Relay and the ability to create ECDSA-based accounts we are able to use Ethers.js while developing on Hedera.

Since covering the entirety of Ethers.js is outside the scope of this quest, please refer to our module on Ethers.js for Blockchain Interaction if you would like to learn more about Ethers.js.

We’ll be filling up the necessary functions in the subsequent steps to see how we can use the Ether.js library to connect our frontend application to our deployed smart contract.

Step 6: Importing Customer Account
We’ll be needing another account to play the role of the customer. Since the customer account will need HBAR to pay for transaction fees in the network as well as have sufficient balance to pay for the lock up amount for the duration of the car lending, let’s create another Hedera Developer Portal and use that as our customer account.
First, head to the Hedera Developer Portal and sign out of the account you used for the Merchant account. 

Here’s a tip for an easy method to ‘creating’ another email account if you’re using Gmail - simply add +1 to your email account name right before the @ in your gmail address and Gmail will ‘create’ a new email address for you. Emails received will still be sent to your original email. For example, if your email address is stackietom@gmail.com, simply enter stackietom+1@gmail.com when signing up for a new Hedera Developer Portal account and the verification email will be sent to stackietom@gmail.com. 

Once you’ve logged in to your new Hedera Developer Portal account, press on the respective buttons to create your testnet account. Once those have been generated, copy your ECDSA HEX Encoded Private Key and import it into your MetaMask wallet (refer to Quest 8 Step 11 if you require a refresher on how to do so). After you’ve imported the account, rename this new account in MetaMask to Customer.


Leave your Hedera Developer Portal open, we’ll be using it in the next step.

In this step, we’re going to set up the environment variables that’ll be needed for the subsequent steps. We’ll need to have several things open here:
  1. .env file (in the quest-9-frontend/hedera-campaign folder)
  2. store-information.txt (in the quest-8-backend folder)
  3. Hedera Developer Portal account of your merchant
  4. Hedera Developer Portal account of your customer

Here’s how we’ll be populating the information within the .env file. Follow along carefully! 
  • REACT_APP_SC_ADDRESS - the value of smart contract address in store-information.txt
  • REACT_APP_FT_ADDRESS - the value of fungible token address in store-information.txt
  • REACT_APP_NFT_ADDRESS - the value of NFT address in store-information.txt
  • REACT_APP_TOPIC_ID - the value of topic id in store-information.txt
  • REACT_APP_MERCHANT_PRIVATE_KEY - the ED25519 DER Encoded Private Key of your MERCHANT’s Hedera Developer Portal account
  • REACT_APP_MERCHANT_ID - the ED25519 Account ID of your MERCHANT’s Hedera Developer Portal account
  • REACT_APP_MERCHANT_ADDRESS - the ECDSA EVM Address of your MERCHANT’s Hedera Developer Portal account
  • REACT_APP_CUSTOMER_ACCOUNT_ID - the ECDSA Account ID of your CUSTOMER’s Hedera Developer Portal account

After you’re done filling up the information, your .env file should look similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. Double check to make sure that you copied the correct values from your Hedera Developer Portal accounts into your .env file! Note that you should be using the ECDSA account ID for your customer, not ED25519.

Step 8: Connect Wallet & Create Contract Instance
In this step, we’ll be adding in the functionality to allow wallet connectivity to our frontend application. We’ll also be seeing how we can instantiate a contract instance that we can use to interact with our deployed smart contract.
const provider = new ethers.providers.Web3Provider(window.ethereum, "any"); await provider.send("eth_requestAccounts", []); const signer = provider.getSigner(); signer.getAddress().then(setDefaultAccount); window.ethereum.on("accountsChanged", changeConnectedAccount); const contractInstance = new ethers.Contract(scAddress, MerchantBackend.abi, signer); setContract(contractInstance);

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 4 - connect wallet.

const provider = new ethers.providers.Web3Provider(window.ethereum, "any"); const signer = provider.getSigner(); signer.getAddress().then(setDefaultAccount); const contractInstance = new ethers.Contract(scAddress, MerchantBackend.abi, signer); setContract(contractInstance);

Then, copy the code above and paste it under Part 5 - create contract instance.

Providers and Signers are Ethers.js concepts, so don’t be alarmed if it looks unfamiliar to you. Essentially a provider instance is an abstraction of a connection to the blockchain network, providing a concise and consistent interface to access standard node functionalities. 

On the other hand, a signer is an abstraction of an account on the network. Signers can be used to sign messages and transactions, as well as send signed transactions to the network to execute state-changing operations.

What we’re doing in our code is creating a provider instance and using that to generate a signer instance. Then, we create a contract instance of our deployed smart contract by providing the contract address, contract ABI and our signer object. Recall that the contract ABI can be taken from the MerchantBackend.json file we created earlier. We can then use this contract instance whenever we want to interact with our deployed smart contract.

Now let’s see if our code works! In your terminal, make sure you’re in the hedera-campaign folder and run the command below to start up your frontend application.

After running the command, a new tab should automatically appear in your browser. If it doesn’t open automatically, you’ll need to manually visit the site localhost:3000/ in your browser. 

A MetaMask popup should appear, asking you to choose which account you want to connect to the webpage. Scroll to the bottom of the list and check that the Merchant account is selected. Then, press on ‘Next’ and ‘Connect’. After your wallet is connected to the page, your page should look similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. You might need to manually refresh the page if the page doesn’t refresh by itself.

This is how the platform looks when the merchant is using it. There are two pages - Add Car and Give Score. The Add Car page is used when the merchant is adding a new car to his fleet (i.e. minting a new NFT). The Give Score page will be used to give REP tokens to customers after they’ve returned a borrowed car.

Step 9: Adding a New Car
Now let’s see how we can create the function to allow the merchant to add a new car (i.e. mint a new NFT). Copy the code below and paste it under Part 6 - add new car.
const tx = await contract.mintNFT(nftAddress, [Buffer.from(cid)], {     gasLimit: 1_000_000,    });    await tx.wait();

We’ll be using the contract instance which we created in the previous step. Recall that in our deployed smart contract, we have a function called mintNFT() that allows us to mint a new NFT each time it’s called. 

This function takes in two parameters as input - the address of our NFT collection (taken from .env file) and the CID of the new NFT to be minted (the merchant will input this when calling this function). We’ll call this function by using the dot (.) notation. Then, we’ll wait for the transaction to be processed.

Recall that every action on our DApp should be logged as messages on the Topic we created in Quest 8. Let’s see how we can add that to our create car action. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 7 - submit add new car logs to topic.

new TopicMessageSubmitTransaction()     .setTopicId(topicId)     .setMessage(      `{    type: Minting,    accountAddr: ${defaultAccount},    tokenId: ${nftId}   }`     )     .execute(client);

We’ll be using the TopicMessageSubmitTransaction API from the Hashgraph JS SDK to submit the message to the topic. If you’ve completed Quest 7, then this should be familiar to you.

Now let’s see our code in action! Let’s try adding two new cars to the merchant’s fleet of cars. Below are the links of the CID of the metadata JSON files of the two cars we’ll be using. Recall from Quest 5 that the metadata JSON file contains information about the NFT such as the name of the NFT collection, the serial number of the NFT, description, etc.). For EACH link (i.e. you’ll need to add 2 cars), copy and paste it into the field on your webpage. Then, press on the ‘Submit’ button. A MetaMask wallet popup should appear asking you to confirm the transaction. Step 10: Associating Tokens
Recall that before accounts can receive tokens (fungible or non-fungible), they first need to be associated with the token. When the customer borrows a car, the NFT will be transferred to the customer’s account. Therefore we’ll need to first associate the customer account with the NFT. 
Later on, since the merchant will be assigning a reputation score to the customer (i.e. transferring REP to the customer account, which is a fungible token), the customer’s account will need to be associated with REP as well.

Let’s see how we can do that!

const provider = new ethers.providers.Web3Provider(window.ethereum, "any");   await provider.send("eth_requestAccounts", []);   const signer = provider.getSigner();   const abi = ["function associate()"];   const contract = new ethers.Contract(id, abi, signer);   try {    const transactionResult = await contract.associate();    return transactionResult.hash;   } catch (error) {    console.warn(error.message ? error.message : error);    return null;   }

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 8 - associate token. Here’s what this chunk of code does - first, we use Ethers.js to instantiate a contract instance contract by using our deployed smart contract address, ABI and signer object. Then, we call the associate function directly on the token to associate the current MetaMask account (i.e. the Customer) with the token.

Note that since we’re associating the customer’s account, we’ll need to sign this transaction using the Customer’s account in MetaMask. Think of this as the customer saying “yes, I authorize my account to be associated to this token collection”.

const mirrorNodeClient = new MirrorNodeClient("testnet"); return await mirrorNodeClient   .getAccountInfo(customerAccount)   .then((acc) => {   const associatedTokensList = acc.balance.tokens;   return associatedTokensList.some((token) => token.token_id === id);   })   .catch((rejectErr) => {   console.log("Could not get token balance", rejectErr);   });

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 9 - check token association. The purpose of this function is to check whether our token association has been successful. To do this, we can make a mirror node query to the accounts AP (recall that we learnt this in Quest 7).

Now that we’ve prepared the functions, let’s see how we can make use of them in the next step!
Step 11: Borrowing a Car
Let’s see how we can make use of the functions we prepared in the previous step.
if (!(await isAssociated(tokenSolidityAddress))) {    await associateToken(tokenSolidityAddress);   } if (!(await isAssociated(ftAddress))) {    await associateToken(ftAddress);   }

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 10 - check if tokens are associated, associate them if not. These are 2 simple if statements that we’ll be using at the start of our borrowCar function to first check if the tokens have been associated with the customer’s account. If the tokens have yet to be associated, then it’ll call the associateToken function to do the token associations.

Now let’s see how we can allow customers to borrow cars!

const tx = await contract.borrowing(tokenSolidityAddress, serial, {     value: ethers.utils.parseEther("1000"),     gasLimit: 2_000_000,    });    await tx.wait();

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 11 - borrow new car. Very similar to what we did for creating a new car, we’ll enable the car borrowing functionality by interacting with a function on our deployed smart contract. Using the contract instance, we access the borrowing function via dot (.) notation. Then we pass in two arguments - the address of the NFT collection tokenSolidityAddress and the serial number serial of the NFT that the customer wishes to borrow. 

Note that we also specify a value of 1000 to be submitted along with the transaction. This refers to the 1000 HBAR lockup amount required from the customer for the duration of the car lending.

new TopicMessageSubmitTransaction()     .setTopicId(topicId)     .setMessage(      `{   type: Borrowing,   accountAddr: ${defaultAccount},   tokenId: ${AccountId.fromSolidityAddress(tokenSolidityAddress)},   serial: ${serial}  }`     )     .execute(client);

We’ll also be logging the action of car borrowing to our topic. Copy the code above and paste it under Part 12 - submit borrow car logs to topic.

Now let’s try borrowing a car! We’ll need to approve 3 transactions in our MetaMask wallet. The first transaction is to approve the token association of the NFT, the second transaction is to approve the token association of the fungible token, and the third is to call the borrow function in the smart contract. Let’s try it out!



First, press on the ‘Borrow’ button of any one of the cars to borrow it. For our first transaction (token association of the NFT) you’ll need to set the Max base fee to 2000 and Gas limit to 800000 (refer to image above), then wait for the gas fees to load from the JSON RPC URL before pressing on the confirmation button.



After a few seconds, MetaMask should prompt you with the second transaction to approve (token associate of the fungible token). After a few seconds, MetaMask should prompt you with the last transaction to approve - the borrow function of our deployed smart contract. After the transaction goes through, you should see that the car has shifted from the Borrow Car page to the Car Returning page (refer to image in ‘Expected output’). This is because the ownership of the car has shifted from the merchant to the customer and action is now on the customer to return the car. 


Also, if you open up your MetaMask wallet, you’ll see that the Customer account has ~1000 HBAR lesser in balance since 1000 HBAR has been transferred to the merchant’s smart contract (refer to image above).﻿

Step 12: Returning a Car
Awesome work so far! Now let’s see how we can return the car back to the merchant. 
const provider = new ethers.providers.Web3Provider(window.ethereum, "any");    await provider.send("eth_requestAccounts", []);    const signer = provider.getSigner();    const abi = ["function approve(address _spender, uint256 _value) public returns (bool success)"];    const ethContract = new ethers.Contract(tokenSolidityAddress, abi, signer);    try {     const transactionResult = await ethContract.approve(scAddress, serial);     await transactionResult.wait();    } catch (error) {     console.warn(error.message ? error.message : error);    }

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 13 - give SC allowance. We’ll need to do 1 additional step before we’re able to proceed with the actual returning of the car - approving an allowance given to the smart contract. If you’re familiar with working with common token standards (e.g. ERC20) in EVM compatible blockchains, then this should be a familiar concept to you.

In layman terms, what’s happening here is the customer telling the smart contract “yes, I allow you to take out tokens from this token collection from my account”. We use Ethers.js to instantiate a contract instance ethContract, which we then use to approve the smart contract of spending the particular NFT that the customer is intending to return. 

Now that the smart contract has been granted approval to pull the NFT token from the customer’s account, we can go ahead and add in the code that actually facilitates the returning of the car back to the merchant!

const tx = await contract.returning(tokenSolidityAddress, serial, {     gasLimit: 1_000_000,    });    await tx.wait();

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 14 - return car. This code is very similar to what we did when we were borrowing the car. This time however, we’re calling the returning function of our smart contract instead. Since the customer is returning the vehicle, there will be no HBAR transferring needed.

new TopicMessageSubmitTransaction()     .setTopicId(topicId)     .setMessage(      `{   type: Returning,   accountAddr: ${defaultAccount},   tokenId: ${tokenSolidityAddress},   serial: ${serial}  }`     )     .execute(client);

We’ll also be logging the return car action to our topic. Copy the code above and paste it under Part 15 - submit return car logs to topic.

Now let’s try returning the car! First, head back to the web app and open the ‘Return Car’ tab. We’ll need to sign 2 transactions in our MetaMask wallet. The first transaction is to give an allowance to the smart contract to allow it to transfer the car NFT. The second transaction is to call the returning function of our smart contract.



First, press on the ‘Return’ button. For our first transaction, you’ll need to set the Max base fee to 2000 and Gas limit to 800000 (refer to image above), then wait for the gas fees to load from the JSON RPC URL before pressing on the confirmation button. 



After a few seconds, MetaMask should prompt you with the second transaction to sign. For this transaction, you’ll need to set the Max base fee to 2000 and Gas limit to 1000000 (refer to image above), then wait for the gas fees to load from the JSON RPC URL before pressing on the confirmation button. 

After the transaction gets processed by the network, you’ll see that the car can no longer be found in the Car Returning Page. That’s because the car has been returned back to the merchant. If you toggle to the ‘Borrow Car’ tab, you’ll see that the car can once again be found there, ready to be borrowed again.


Moreover, if you open your MetaMask wallet, you’ll see that the 1000 HBAR has been released from the smart contract back to our wallet (refer to image above). Awesome! We got our locked up funds back since we’ve successfully returned the car.
Step 13: Giving REP Tokens
Now that the car has been returned to the merchant, the last piece of our project is for the merchant to assign some REP tokens to the customer, 0 representing a poor lending experience (e.g. car returned with scratches, car returned late, etc.) and 5 representing a good lending experience. First, let’s see how we can query for the amount of the customer’s REP tokens.
await fetch(`https://testnet.mirrornode.hedera.com/api/v1/accounts/${defaultAccount}/tokens?token.id=${ftId}`)      .then((response) => response.json())      .then((data) => {       if (!data.tokens[0]) {        setScore(0);        return;       }       setScore(data.tokens[0].balance);      });

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 16 - get reputation token score. Here we’re making yet another mirror node API call to query for information from the Hedera network. This time, it's to query for the current account’s balance of the REP fungible token.

await fetch(`https://testnet.mirrornode.hedera.com/api/v1/accounts/${customer}`)     .then((response) => response.json())     .then(async (data) => {      console.log(data.evm_address);      const tx = await contract.scoring(data.evm_address, score, {       gasLimit: 1_000_000,      });      await tx.wait();     });

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 17 - give reputation tokens. Again, we’ll be interacting with a function in our deployed smart contract for this (the scoring function). However, you may have noticed that the code this time round looks slightly more complicated compared to what we’ve been doing. This is because we first need to use the mirror node API to fetch the account’s EVM address. We then pass in the EVM address as one of the arguments when calling the scoring function of our smart contract.

new TopicMessageSubmitTransaction()     .setTopicId(topicId)     .setMessage(      `{    type: Scoring,    accountAddr: ${customer},    tokenId: ${ftId.toString()},    amount: ${1}   }`     )     .execute(client);

Copy the code above and paste it under Part 18 - submit give reputation tokens logs to topic. This code is largely similar to what we’ve been doing for the previous situations where we log messages to our topic.

Now let’s test it out!



In your MetaMask, change back to the Merchant account. Then, on your webpage, open up the ‘Give Score’ tab. You should be able to see the list of customers that have borrowed from the merchant. Since we’ve only borrowed with one account so far, you should only be able to see one customer (refer to image above). Note that it might take up to a few minutes before we’re able to query the information from the mirror node API, so don’t be alarmed if you’re not able to see the customer card on your screen immediately.



Input 4 into the ‘Score Amount’ field and press on ‘Give Reputation Tokens’. Again, you’ll need to set the max base fee to 2000 (refer to image above) and wait for the gas fees to load from the JSON RPC URL before confirming the transaction. 

After the transaction goes through, change back to the Customer account in your MetaMask wallet. You should be able to see that the number of reputation tokens has changed to 4! Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference on how your webpage should look like.

To double check that the REP tokens have indeed been transferred to the Customer account, let’s import the REP tokens into our MetaMask wallet. 

Open your MetaMask wallet and press on ‘Import tokens’ (at the bottom of the Assets tab). Then, copy the value of REACT_APP_FT_ADDRESS from your .env file and paste it into the ‘Token contract address’ field. If the ‘Token symbol’ field does not automatically populate itself, then input ‘REP’ into the field and press on ‘Add custom token’ and ‘Import tokens’. 

You should be able to see that the Customer account has a balance of 4 REP tokens, similar to the image below. Awesome!

Step 14: Viewing Logged Messages on Topic
Throughout this quest, we’ve been consistently logging messages to our Topic, but you’ll notice that we haven’t actually viewed these messages yet. Let’s check them out in this step!
Open up the Hashscan block explorer. Then, copy your topic ID (can be found in store-information.txt) and search for it in the block explorer. You’ll see that all our messages have been logged in chronological order in the topic, similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. 

Let’s do a short recap of the actions we performed in this quest:
  1. First, as the merchant, we added two new cars to our fleet (mint two NFTs)
  2. Then, we associated the customer’s account with the NFT and fungible token collection
  3. After that was done, the customer could proceed to borrow a car from the merchant
  4. Before returning the car, the customer approved the smart contract to an allowance of its NFTs, thus the smart contract was able to pull the NFT from the customer’s account and transfer it to the merchant
  5. Lastly, as the merchant, we scored the customer and minted 4 REP tokens to the customer

Step 15: Summary of Capstone Project
And with that, we’ve reached the end of the capstone project (and the campaign)! Through this project, we’ve seen firsthand how the different functionalities of the Hedera Network Services can be used together in the context of a DApp. 
In Quest 8, we learnt how we can use the Hedera Smart Contract Service to create and deploy a smart contract that facilitates the functions needed in our project. In particular, we created a fungible token collection (REP) and an NFT collection (CAR). We also created functions in our smart contract that handled the borrowing and returning of cars as well as the issuing of REP tokens. Lastly, we created a topic using the Hedera Consensus Service that was subsequently used in this quest to log activities that occurred in our DApp.

In this quest, we saw how we can create a frontend that allows users to interact with the smart contract we deployed in Quest 8. In particular, we used the React framework to build the web application and the Ethers.js library to interact with our deployed smart contract. We learnt important concepts such as how to allow connectivity of a wallet to a frontend application, how to use the mirror node API service to query for information, how to associate tokens, how to approve a token allowance and how to interact with deployed smart contracts.

Over the course of both these quests, we also learnt how we can use the MetaMask wallet in the context of developing in Hedera. 

Hope you had fun learning about how to build cool stuff on Hedera!
